faqs:
  - q: "When is a Cockapoo considered senior?"
    a: "As a small-medium crossbreed (typically 5–11kg) Cockapoos are long-lived — often 13–16 years — and tend to reach 'senior' status later than a big dog, around 9–11 years. Don't go by the calendar alone: greying around that curly muzzle, stiffer mornings, slower walks and a calmer temperament are the real markers. The crossbreed advantage (hybrid vigour) often means a Cockapoo stays sprightly into old age, but the lifelong brief — unpredictable food reactions inherited from both parents, ear flare-ups from the Cocker side and a coat that needs omega support from the Poodle side — doesn't retire. The senior shift (more joint support, fewer calories, easier digestion) layers on top of it."
  - q: "How much should I feed a senior Cockapoo per day?"
    a: "Less than you fed them as a bouncy adult. An adult Cockapoo (5–11kg) eats roughly 100–200g of dry food a day depending on size within the range; a steadier senior needs fewer calories than that. As a rough June-2026 guide, feeding an 8kg senior as its sole diet costs about £0.40–0.70/day on quality grain-free kibble, £0.60–0.95/day air-dried, or £1.00–1.70/day on fresh-cooked subscription — far gentler on the wallet than the same maths for a big dog. The honest method is to weigh meals on a kitchen scale, weigh your dog monthly, and adjust to keep the ribs easily felt under that fluffy coat — which hides weight gain remarkably well."
  - q: "What should I look for in food for an older Cockapoo?"
    a: "Five things, the first three carried over from the breed's lifelong brief and now more important: limited-ingredient, low-trigger nutrition (grain-free, a named single protein — Cockapoos inherit unpredictable sensitivities and many react to chicken, grains or artificial additives); omega-3 for that curly Poodle-inherited coat, which gets drier and more prone to matting with age; and tight calorie control under a coat that hides the waistline. Then add the senior layer: joint support (glucosamine, chondroitin, omega-3 for small joints prone to patellar luxation and the arthritis age brings) and easy digestibility with high palatability — gently-cooked fresh, air-dried or cold-pressed recipes sit better on an ageing gut and tempt a fading appetite."
  - q: "Why is fresh food a realistic choice for a senior Cockapoo?"
    a: "Cost. Fresh-cooked subscriptions are priced largely by how much your dog eats, so the premium over kibble scales with size — punishing for a 35kg Labrador but very manageable for a 5–11kg Cockapoo eating a smaller, senior-reduced portion. A senior Cockapoo is exactly the dog where the benefits of fresh feeding (high moisture, strong aroma, soft texture for ageing teeth, easy digestion) line up with an older dog's needs while the bill stays modest. For many senior Cockapoo owners, full fresh feeding or a fresh topper is the single best-value upgrade you can make — and the limited, named-ingredient recipes suit a crossbreed with unpredictable reactions."
  - q: "Do senior Cockapoos still get ear infections, and can food help?"
    a: "Often, yes — the Cocker-inherited long, hairy, low-hanging ear canals trap moisture, and an ageing immune system copes less well, so flare-ups can persist or worsen into old age. Food won't cure an ear infection, but for the many Cockapoos whose flare-ups are driven by food allergy, a grain-free, single novel-protein diet (turkey is a popular clean alternative to chicken) can genuinely reduce how often the canals inflame. Pair diet with regular ear cleaning, drying after swims and keeping the ear hair trimmed, and see your vet for any active infection — diet is one half of the equation."
  - q: "My senior Cockapoo's coat has gone dry and matts more easily. Can diet help?"
    a: "Partly. An ageing Cockapoo's curly, Poodle-inherited coat naturally produces less oil and can become drier, duller and quicker to matt. Diet is one lever: omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids (from fish oil, salmon or named animal fats) support skin-barrier function and coat condition from the inside, and good-quality named-meat protein supplies the building blocks for healthy hair. You'll see the difference over weeks, not days. Pair it with regular grooming — an older dog still needs that low-shedding coat clipped and brushed, and a dry senior coat matts faster — and rule out an underactive thyroid with your vet if the coat changes suddenly, as it's common in older dogs and mimics a dietary problem."
  - q: "Should I switch my senior Cockapoo to a 'senior' labelled food?"
    a: "Not automatically — the 'senior' label isn't regulated and quality varies hugely. What matters is the profile: moderate calories, joint support, adequate named protein, omega-3 for coat, and easy digestibility, all on a low-trigger, ideally grain-free and limited-ingredient base for an unpredictable crossbreed. A high-quality fresh, air-dried or grain-free adult food that hits those marks can beat a mediocre 'senior' recipe. Whatever you choose, transition gradually over 7–10 days — a Cockapoo's inherited sensitivity means sudden change can upset the gut."
