<h2>How to Choose for Your Senior Cockapoo</h2>

<p>There's no single winner — it depends on your dog, your budget and your kitchen:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Unpredictable tummy or itchy skin?</strong> Prioritise a grain-free, limited-ingredient, single named-protein recipe (turkey over chicken if your dog is reactive) to cut food-driven inflammation — Years, Butternut Box (tailorable) and Forthglade grain-free all fit. The fewer ingredients, the easier to pin down a trigger.</li>
  <li><strong>Recurrent ear flare-ups?</strong> Same grain-free, single-protein approach reduces the food-driven inflammation that thickens those long Cocker-inherited canals. Pair with regular ear cleaning, drying and trimming the ear hair.</li>
  <li><strong>Dry, matting senior coat?</strong> Lean on omega-rich recipes — the steam-cooked fresh brands and fish-inclusive formulas support coat condition from the inside. Rule out an underactive thyroid with your vet if the coat changes suddenly.</li>
  <li><strong>Slipping kneecaps or stiff joints?</strong> Lean on joint support and keep weight down — small joints feel every extra gram. Fresh and cold-pressed recipes plus omega-3 help; pair with your vet's advice if luxation or arthritis is established.</li>
  <li><strong>Fussy or fading appetite / worn teeth?</strong> Fresh or air-dried wins on palatability, moisture and soft texture — and for a Cockapoo-sized senior the premium is small. Years and Butternut Box are the most tempting.</li>
  <li><strong>On a budget?</strong> Pure Pet Food or Forthglade grain-free give excellent senior nutrition without the premium frozen-fresh price.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Senior Cockapoos vs Adult Cockapoos: What Changes</h2>

<p>If you've been feeding a good adult food, the senior shift is a recalibration rather than a reinvention. The limited-ingredient, low-trigger, omega-for-coat brief stays exactly as it was — that crossbreed unpredictability doesn't retire with age, it gets a little touchier. What's added is <strong>fewer calories for the same or better protein</strong> (your Cockapoo is moving less but still needs muscle to protect ageing joints), more emphasis on joint support for small luxation-prone knees, and a tilt toward digestibility and palatability as the gut, teeth and appetite age. The happy twist that comes with a small-medium breed: because a senior Cockapoo eats less, the fresh-food premium shrinks just as its benefits (moisture, aroma, soft texture) matter most — the value case actually strengthens with age. We dig into that in our <a href="/senior-dog-food-cost-value-uk/">senior dog food cost vs value guide</a>. For raising one from the start, our <a href="/best-food-for-cockapoo-puppies/">best food for Cockapoo puppies guide</a> covers the start-simple, watch-for-reactions feeding that pays off later; and for the wider senior view across breeds, our <a href="/best-senior-dog-food-uk/">best senior dog food guide</a> goes deeper on the science. Allergy-prone seniors may also find our <a href="/best-dog-food-sensitive-stomach-uk/">sensitive stomach &amp; skin guide</a> useful.</p>

<h2>How Much to Feed — and Transitioning a Senior Cockapoo</h2>

<p>Portion is where most senior Cockapoos slip — that fluffy coat hides a creeping waistline — so feed calories, not cupfuls: our <a href="/how-much-to-feed-senior-dog/">how much to feed a senior dog guide</a> turns calorie needs into grams of kibble, wet or fresh, and the <a href="/dog-food-calculator/?breed=cockapoos">dog food calculator</a> will prefill a typical Cockapoo weight for you. When you change foods, switch over <strong>7–10 days</strong>, mixing increasing amounts of the new food into the old, and slow down if you see loose stools — an older Cockapoo's inherited sensitivity means sudden change can upset the gut. Measure every meal on a scale, count treats in the daily total, feel for the ribs under the coat, and weigh your dog monthly. And whenever a senior Cockapoo's appetite, weight, coat or toileting changes noticeably and doesn't settle, book a vet check; at this age, food is only part of the picture.</p>

